Introduction¶

This project aims to analyse the Medical Appointment No Shows dataset. This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. Several characteristics of the patient are included in each row.

The variables included in this dataset are:

  • PatientId: Identification of a patient
  • AppointmentID: Identification of each appointment
  • Gender: Male or Female
  • ScheduledDay: The day of the actual appointment, when they have to visit the doctor
  • AppointmentDay: The day someone called or registered the appointment
  • Age: How old is the patient
  • Neighbourhood: Where the appointment takes place
  • Scholarship: True or False, indicates if the patient is in the Bolsa Familia program
  • Hipertension: True or False
  • Diabetes: True or False
  • Alcoholism: True or False
  • Handcap: True or False
  • SMS_received: 1 or more messages sent to the patient
  • No-show: "No" indicates if the patient showed up to their appointment and "Yes" if they didn't show up

Having No-show as dependent variable, the preliminary questions for this project are:

  1. What factors determine if a patient will show up to the medical appointment?

    1. Location/scholarship
    2. Diseases and Received SMS
    3. Waiting time between the scheduled day and the appointment day
    4. Gender/Age

  2. What factors determine if a patient will not show up to the medical appointment?

    1. Location/scholarship
    2. Diseases and Received SMS
    3. Waiting time between the scheduled day and the appointment day
    4. Gender/Age

After generating the descriptive statistics and checked the period range:

  1. Age present an odd minimum value (-1) and an odd maximum (115);
  2. The majority (75%) of patients are 55 years old and the minority (25%) are 18 years old;
  3. The average age is 37 years old;
  4. The scheduled day period goes from November 2015 to June 2016;
  5. The appointment day period goes from April 2016 to June 2016.

The new histograms show that:

  • Patients with just one appointment are more common;
  • Waiting days are clearly skewed to the left, having more patients with immediate appointment.

The correlation matrix does not show any particular relation between variables, thus, we are going to analyse the dataset base on distribution and descriptive statistics to extract theories. After cleaning the data and creating two new category's columns, we have decided to keep age and waiting time in case we need to use them afterwards and, we added a new independent variable to analyse against out dependent variable.

Hence, the questions that we look to answer are:

  1. What factors determine if a patient will show up to the medical appointment?

    1. Location/scholarship
    2. Diseases and Received SMS
    3. Waiting time between the scheduled day and the appointment day
    4. Gender/Age
    5. Multiple appointments for same patient**

  2. What factors determine if a patient will not show up to the medical appointment?

    1. Location/scholarship
    2. Diseases and Received SMS
    3. Waiting time between the scheduled day and the appointment day
    4. Gender/Age
    5. Multiple appointments for same patient

Conclusions¶

This project aims to analyse the characteristics of the dataset to understand which variables affect a patient to show or not show up in their medical appointment.

There is no correlation evident between variables, for this reason, we carried an analysis of the properties of each independent variable in relation with showing or not showing.

Firstly, more patients are prone to show up (count 88298) than miss the appointment (22319). Additionally, the age is slightly higher in the show-up group (average 38) in comparison with patients no showing up (average 33). Lastly, the average waiting days for patients showing up is lesser (8 days average), with 50% of the population waiting just 1 day, versus the average of no showing up (15 days), having 50% of the population waiting 10 days.

Looking at the location, both top 1 neighbourhood is Jardim Camburi. Both cases, the percentage of people without scholarship is higher than with it. However, comparing those percentages, patients that do not show up, have a slightly greater percentage of scholarship -0.1%, whereas showup patients 0.09%-.

Besides, it is interesting to note that the neighbourhood with more scholarships, in both samples, is Ilha do Prncipe. Finally, add to this point, that only one neighboorhood with scholarship in the patients showing up is also part of the top 5: Resistencia.

Next, analysing the diseases and the SMS reception, both groups present high cases of patients with hypertension (especially for patients showing up), and only patients showing up have a high number patients with diabetes. Apart from that, receiving SMS in both cases present an elevated number.

The following section enlights that there is a higher chance of patients showing up when the appointment is rather immediate, whereas they will not show up if they have to wait between one week and one month.

Looking at gender and age, for both situations, adults and women are more predisposed to either show or not show. Hence, doing inferential theories based on gender and age is not advised.

Ultimately, there are more patients with a unique appointment, however, in both cases, the waiting time is higher than when the patient has multiple appointments.

All in all, those characteristics that are present in both categories can be discarded as factors that will make a patient more prone to show or not show up. The only differences could be that patients with diabetes are more prone to do not miss their appointment and that the extended waiting time, the likely to miss it.

Limitations that we found:

- the data type boolean makes correlation more difficult to check;
- besides, there is a clear uncertainty of relevant importance of the diseases, because we do not know how this data is gathered and how can be categorised.

Further analysis:

- It would be interesting to have access to the socio-economic database to understand how the different neighbourhoods are important;
- It is necessary to apply regression analysis to get deeper information on the relationship between variables.
